Position Description
GitHub Enterprise is used by large companies to help them build great software. Our Enterprise Support team is there to help them keep their appliances running smoothly. Technical Account Managers give some of our largest customers a primary point of contact with our support team. These customers often require unique solutions for scaling and integrating with their infrastructure. As a Technical Account Manager, you'll work side-by-side with them to help them succeed and thrive.Responsibilities:Work closely with a small number of GitHub Enterprise customers, helping them to be more successful with GitHub over time. You'll learn about their successes and challenges, share their feedback within GitHub, and advocate for their interests.Help solve often highly complex support tickets, usually opened by customer system administrators, using your own technical skills and coordinating responses from our infrastructure and engineering teams. Tickets can include investigation of load or networking issues, debugging application errors, discussing feature requests, and many other issues.Respond to emails and phone calls from your customer accounts.Initiate outgoing contact with your customer accounts to, for example, coordinate upgrades, communicate upcoming features, and ensure their installation is running smoothly.Liaise with our engineering team to prioritize issues and development, and our documentation team to improve customer-facing resources.Be available during business hours for urgent responses to customer outages.Qualifications:Significant experience working with and troubleshooting Linux serversEnthusiasm for working directly with customersAbility to communicate technical information clearlyStellar English and grammar skillsAbility to look through and understand code, especially Ruby and BashBonus:Familiarity with production-level virtualization, either cloud based (e.g. AWS, Azure) or on premises (e.g. VMware ESX, KVM)Familiarity with Git and GitHubExperience with phone supportAbout GitHubWho we areGitHub is the best place to share code with friends, co-workers, classmates, and complete strangers. Over eight million people use GitHub to build amazing things together. With the collaborative features of GitHub.com, our desktop and mobile apps, and GitHub Enterprise, it has never been easier for individuals and teams to write better code, faster., and we're looking for the right people to grow with us!Why you should joinWorking at GitHub is, to put it simply, a special slice of the universe. We're committed to transparency, collaboration, experimentation, and always staying classy. Because of this unique perspective, we've established one of the most flexible and well designed physical workspaces around that encourages you to work as you work best. Right now, over 60% of our employees are based outside of our San Francisco (SOMA) headquarters and work according to how they get their best stuff done. Ensuring that GitHubbers are healthy, motivated, focused and creative is how GitHub stays awesome. Part of this is ensuring that our * are out of this world.In a nutshell, we've built and are growing a place where we truly love working, and we think you will too.GitHub is made up of people with many different backgrounds and lifestyles, and we like it that way. We invite applications from people of all stripes. We don't discriminate against employees or applicants based on gender identity or expression, sexual orientation, race, religion, age, national origin, citizenship, pregnancy status, veteran status, or any other differences that people imagine to discriminate against one another. Also, if you have a disability, please let us know if there's anything we can do to make the interview process better for you; we're happy to accommodate.Please note that benefits vary by country, if you have any questions don't hesitate to ask your recruiter!










 











